shire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pershale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Perschall</b>, a variant of <b>Parschall</b> (see   Parshall  ); alternatively, a variant of <b>Perschel</b>, from a pet form of <b>Persch</b>, a short form of   Berthold   or   Peter   in the border area with Czechia."],"variants":[{"name":"Parshall","meanings":["Americanized form of South German <b>Parschall</b>, a variant of <b>Parschalk</b>, a status name for a freeholder (a freeman with few service obligations), from Middle High German <i>bar</i> ‘naked’, ‘free from, apparent’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant, man’. See   Pershall  .","English: variant of   Pearsall  ."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"(Mrs. ) De Pershale was born about 1215, in France as the daughter of Miss Barrett. She had at least 1 son with Richard De Pershale."},"et":{"ABT 1215–":"umbes 1215–Surnud","1184–Male":"1184–Surnud","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1215–1250":"1215–1250","1229–1300":"1229–1300","1142–Female":"1142–Surnud","1215":"1215","1300":"1300","1142":"1142","ABT 1215":"umbes 1215","1250":"1250","1184":"1184","Abt 1229":"umbes 1229","1229":"1229","of,Swynerton,,France":"Prantsusmaa","Swynnerton, Staffordshire, England":"Swynnerton, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1215–":"noin 1215–Kuollut","1184–Male":"1184–Kuollut","1215–Female":"1215–Kuollut","1215–1250":"1215–1250","1229–1300":"1229–1300","1142–Female":"1142–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1300":"1300","1142":"1142","ABT 1215":"noin 1215","1250":"1250","1184":"1184","Abt 1229":"noin 1229","1229":"1229","of,Swynerton,,France":"Ranska","Swynnerton, Staffordshire, England":"Swynnerton, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1215–":"environ 1215–Décédée","1184–Male":"1184–Décédé","1215–Female":"1215–Décédée","1215–1250":"1215–1250","1229–1300":"1229–1300","1142–Female":"1142–Décédée","1215":"1215","1300":"1300","1142":"1142","ABT 1215":"environ 1215","1250":"1250","1184":"1184","Abt 1229":"environ 1229","1229":"1229","of,Swynerton,,France":"France","Swynnerton, Staffordshire, England":"Swynnerton, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"(Mrs. ) De Pershale est née environ 1215, à France, fille de Miss Barrett. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Richard De Pershale."},"de":{"ABT 1215–":"um 1215–Verstorben","1184–Male":"1184–Verstorben"